WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.110 --> 00:00:08.360
This is Democracy Now!, democracynow.org,
The War and Peace Report.

00:00:08.360 --> 00:00:09.360
I’m Amy Goodman.

00:00:09.360 --> 00:00:14.560
A shocking new report finds at least a third
of the Himalayan ice cap will melt by the

00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:19.370
end of the century due to climate change,
even if the world’s most ambitious environmental

00:00:19.370 --> 00:00:20.750
reforms are implemented.

00:00:20.750 --> 00:00:26.790
The report released Monday by The Hindu Kush
Himalaya Assessment is the culmination of

00:00:26.790 --> 00:00:32.980
half a decade’s work by over 200 scientists,
with an additional 125 experts peer reviewing

00:00:32.980 --> 00:00:34.120
their work.

00:00:34.120 --> 00:00:40.050
It warns rising temperatures in the Himalayas
could lead to mass population displacements,

00:00:40.050 --> 00:00:43.390
as well as catastrophic food and water insecurity.

00:00:43.390 --> 00:00:49.079
The glaciers are a vital water source for
the 250 million people who live in the Hindu

00:00:49.079 --> 00:00:53.739
Kush Himalaya range, which spans from Afghanistan
to Burma.

00:00:53.739 --> 00:00:59.149
The region is home to the most ice in the
world, after Antarctica and the Arctic.

00:00:59.149 --> 00:01:03.350
And over a billion-and-a-half people depend
on the rivers that flow from the Himalayan

00:01:03.350 --> 00:01:04.350
peaks.

00:01:04.350 --> 00:01:09.610
We turn now to the world-renowned environmental
leader and ecologist, who was born in Doon

00:01:09.610 --> 00:01:12.860
Valley in the Himalayan foothills, Dr. Vandana
Shiva.

00:01:12.860 --> 00:01:18.320
She’s an Indian scholar and physicist, as
well as a food sovereignty and seed freedom

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:19.320
advocate.

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:24.880
Dr. Shiva is also an alternative globalization
author who’s written more than 20 books.

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:31.200
Her latest, Oneness vs. the 1% and Who Really
Feeds the World?

00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:36.640
She founded Navdanya, “nine seeds,” a
movement promoting diversity and use of native

00:01:36.640 --> 00:01:37.640
seeds.

00:01:37.640 --> 00:01:43.350
In 1993, Dr. Shiva was recipient of the Alternative
Nobel Peace Prize, the Right Livelihood Award.

00:01:43.350 --> 00:01:45.030
Vandana Shiva, welcome back to Democracy Now!

00:01:45.030 --> 00:01:46.100
VANDANA SHIVA: My joy to be with you again,
Amy.

00:01:46.100 --> 00:01:47.780
AMY GOODMAN: It’s great to have you with
us.

00:01:47.780 --> 00:01:52.250
The title of this book, Oneness vs. the 1%,
explain.

00:01:52.250 --> 00:01:57.330
VANDANA SHIVA: Well, oneness is the recognition
that, A, we are part of one planet, and we

00:01:57.330 --> 00:01:58.990
are one humanity.

00:01:58.990 --> 00:02:04.310
And unless we live with that consciousness
and shape every moment of our production and

00:02:04.310 --> 00:02:08.940
consumption with that consciousness, we are
going to destroy ourselves, which we are.

00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:13.400
The melting of the glaciers is one of the
very severe indicators.

00:02:13.400 --> 00:02:20.260
The 1 percent, of course, is the symbol of
the concentration of wealth under the rules

00:02:20.260 --> 00:02:26.760
of the neoliberal economies, that are basically,
on the one hand, turning every natural resource

00:02:26.760 --> 00:02:28.950
into a war zone.

00:02:28.950 --> 00:02:36.010
Even the Venezuelan issue is really a war
